ood ? <\/p>\n","question_id":16541,"tags":["human-biology","reproduction","eyes","embryology","development"],"score":7,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1863,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1397567964},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/77aec462c91b0bcad1bcd55dbbc98495?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":5411,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5411/adma","reputation":16,"display_name":"Adma"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe87113ced5f370d038b90a43fd1fe1f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":408,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/408/anixx","reputation":909,"display_name":"Anixx","accept_rate":20},"score":0,"post_id":14439,"edited":false,"creation_date":1389598786,"comment_id":19089,"body":"This is called &quot;necrobiosis&quot;."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":14439,"edited":false,"creation_date":1397404591,"comment_id":22293,"body":"isn&#39;t brain death the definition of death in many medical cases?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1HuAu.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6314,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6314/doctor-whom","reputation":876,"display_name":"Doctor Whom"},"score":0,"post_id":14439,"edited":false,"creation_date":1397565036,"comment_id":22383,"body":"Yes, brain death is what medical professionals [generally] use to define death, as modern medicine is often able to keep a human body physiologically functioning for an extended period of time through technology and medication - and it is often possible to do this well past where the body would have originally died on its alone.  This is done when there remains hope that the body will recover and consciousness will return.  However, if additionally cerebral function is also convincingly lost (discussion of how we test for that is another topic), the concept of medical futility comes into play."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/fgVzF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5367,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5367/martin-dinov","reputation":184,"display_name":"Martin Dinov"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1389604422,"creation_date":1389604422,"body":"<p>I think that depends somewhat on how the human dies - in particular on the conditions. If they die in a very cold environment (say at the top of some icy mountain range), they'll freeze and metabolic processes will slow down considerably, and so will cell death. But such hypothermia-based slowing down is a special case. Normally, if your heart stops or you are not getting oxygen to your brain (perhaps due to a stroke), your neurons will start dying pretty quickly. Within many minutes there will certainly be considerable permanent cell loss - certainly within hours. If oxygen is significantly depleted, ATP production will also significantly drop. If this happens, the various ATP-dependent processes will slow to a crawl (including the Na/K ATPase and other ion pumps and channels that are needed for maintaining and changing the voltage difference between the inside and outside of the cell). This in itself is bad enough as a lot of the enzymes and mechanisms that are dependent on the voltage difference will fail (and probably enough of a reason for many cells to start dying), but one of the effects of this is apparently an increase in the extracellular glutamate, which ultimately leads to (via NMDA receptors for example) an influx of calcium ions into the neurons. Too much of the calcium ions is once again toxic for a variety of the processes inside the cell and is an additional and big reason for neuronal cell death.<\/p>\n\n<p>In short, as far as I know, neurons don't have a good time living without sufficient oxygen and therefore after a typical human death.<\/p>\n","answer_id":14451,"question_id":14439,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/14439/will-neurons-live-after-the-death-of-a-human-if-so-how-long","last_activity_date":1397563515,"creation_date":1389561777,"answer_count":1,"title":"Will neurons live after the death of a human? If so, how long?","body":"<p>I don't know if this is correct or not, but I have heard this from a friend and I want to get a clear explanation about this.I hope there is some one who can help me.<\/p>\n","question_id":14439,"tags":["human-biology","neuroscience","neurology"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":466,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1389587365},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b78aed5f7fadf9f6493326c73f9e0b83?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6099,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6099/beletsky","reputation":36,"display_name":"Beletsky"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":2,"post_id":16472,"edited":false,"creation_date":1397157641,"comment_id":22222,"body":"Could you give specific examples of antimalarials that block gap junctions? If they do, I&#39;m pretty sure that this isn&#39;t anything to do with their antimalarial action. Most of the standard drugs interfere with the food vacuole of Plasmodium resulting in haem toxicity."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f8b41b17537f38c6f0523ca2dad02c4e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":784,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/784/tel","reputation":2829,"display_name":"tel","accept_rate":80},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1397531373,"creation_date":1397280310,"body":"<p>I wasn't sure when I first read this, but this is actually a very interesting question. <\/p>\n\n<p>Right now there seem to be two completely divorced lines of inquiry that researchers are pursuing with respect to the antimalarial drugs. <\/p>\n\n<p>One group of researchers is working on working out the mechanism by which say, chloroquine and its ilk bind to and  interfere with the formation of hemazoin (a parasite-friendly form of red blood cell proteins) in the vacuoles of the plasmodium (the parasite that causes malaria). Some folks have recently gotten some pretty reasonable <a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0162013408001141\" rel=\"nofollow\">crystals<\/a> of chloroquine interacting directly with hemazoin. This all provides strong evidence for the view that, as regards killing plasmodium, the most significant interaction for an antimalarial is the one between it and hemazoin.<\/p>\n\n<p>In (probably) unrelated news it was discovered that many of these antimalarials are also potent <a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/98/19/10942.full.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">channel blockers<\/a> of various kinds. I haven't dug into this too deeply yet, but most antimalarial people seem to view the channel blocking activity as a side effect. There are a number of other studies underway right now evaluating the psychological effect of the channel blocking activity of the antimalarials. There's <a href=\"http://www.jbiomedsci.com/content/20/1/77\" rel=\"nofollow\">one out of Iran<\/a> that says that the blocking activity of Mefloquine can be used to ease the symptoms of morphine withdrawal.<\/p>\n\n<p>Another thing to keep in mind is that Mefloquine fell out of favor not due to a decrease in efficacy, but was instead mostly taken out of circulation due to it's (justified) reputation for causing psychotic episodes in patients. So maybe this gap junction blocking stuff could be used to explain Mefloquine psychological side-effects. That would be neat!<\/p>\n","answer_id":16486,"question_id":16472,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1397531373}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16472/why-are-many-anti-malaria-drugs-gap-junction-antagonists","last_activity_date":1397531373,"creation_date":1397155275,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why are many anti-malaria drugs gap junction antagonists?","body":"<p>Why are many anti-malaria drugs gap junction antagonists?<\/p>\n\n<p>My professor recently just mentioned that many of the anti-malaria drugs block gap junctions. i am wondering if this blocking is important for stopping malaria, and how blocking gap junctions is anti-malarial. How does this effect connect to the mechanism of malaria?<\/p>\n","question_id":16472,"tags":["human-biology","pharmacology","malaria","pharmacodynamics"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":54,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1397160687},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/64bcbc6f7b28b061f9b920043f052779?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5203,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5203/yair","reputation":121,"display_name":"Yair"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":16484,"edited":false,"creation_date":1397287636,"comment_id":22252,"body":"Question of physiology are very welcome to our site! There is even a often used tag for that. It is totally on-topic."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/93aaedbb6e98556c9cd8b2f0795c735f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4321,"link":"http://biology.stackexchan