p://www.visualphotos.com/photo/1x8722914/skin_allergy_caused_by_mosquito_bites_049286.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\">visualphotos.com/photo/1x8722914/&hellip;<\/a>  you&#39;ll see the most common presentation of a mosquito bite wheal.  The edges are not well demarcated; rather, there is a fade-away of erythema.  This is as I mentioned largely a result of the limited range of inflammatory cytokines."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1397498254,"creation_date":1397498254,"body":"<p>What you're referring to as a mosquito bite is actually the \"wheal\" (red swollen bump in the skin) that forms from an immune system reaction to antigens (foreign molecules) in the saliva of the mosquito that it leaves behind inside the bite.  It's not technically a toxin, just something that causes an immune reaction.  <\/p>\n\n<p>It's also not an infection, it's inflammation.  Infection might set in if the skin is scratched open and bacteria move in.<\/p>\n\n<p>The reason it's red is that immune cells release cytokines (like histamine and that cause cause edema that leads to swelling, heat, itching, etc - and recruit other cells to do the same.<\/p>\n\n<p>The cytokines that act locally have a range of effect, especially histamine.  The degree of immune reaction determines the size of the wheal and how long it lasts.  Scratching it contributes to irritation and can prolong resolution.  Scratching it open can lead to infection.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16549,"question_id":16484,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16484/why-mosquito-bite-is-confined-to-a-certain-shape","last_activity_date":1397517841,"creation_date":1397262480,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why mosquito bite is confined to a certain shape?","body":"<p>I think this problem should be asked in a physiology forum rather than biology@ stackex but I'll give it a try.\nSo my question is simple - why a mosquito bite is usually confined to a certain shape (shape = red area) and not just disappearing continuously? Can our body cells tolerate some level of antigens without changing color from that?<\/p>\n","question_id":16484,"tags":["cell-biology","physiology","immunology"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":282,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1397517841},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/85ddc411411f3353241b688e9432362e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5732,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5732/abyss-7","reputation":116,"display_name":"abyss.7"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"score":3,"post_id":15066,"edited":false,"creation_date":1392480534,"comment_id":20146,"body":"The functions of Parasympathetic nervous system - Rest and digest !"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/4jVI8.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5702,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5702/manuella","reputation":416,"display_name":"Manuella"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/45195875d9ed18788474bdae5d9d67b8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3827,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3827/skymningen","reputation":1558,"display_name":"skymningen"},"score":0,"post_id":15067,"edited":false,"creation_date":1392629162,"comment_id":20190,"body":"That is a very biased experiment, to say the least. Why, for example, do people then go for a &quot;digestion walk&quot; and actually feel it helps them to digest?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c4690b9a0df8a4c1e35c088b077942e6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6132,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6132/steve-jessop","reputation":320,"d