ote says &quot;bringing together favourable alleles from different chromosomes&quot;, which doesn&#39;t involve crossing over."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":15232,"edited":false,"creation_date":1393018905,"comment_id":20398,"body":"&quot;In meiosis and mitosis, recombination occurs between similar molecules (homologs) of DNA. In meiosis, non-sister homologous chromosomes pair with each other so that recombination characteristically occurs between non-sister homologues. In both meiotic and mitotic cells, recombination between homologous chromosomes is a common mechanism used in DNA repair.&quot; <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_recombination\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_recombination<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":15232,"edited":false,"creation_date":1393151931,"comment_id":20452,"body":"@sigeta I agree with you shigeta. But I don&#39;t think your answer answers my question. I understand that if a highly beneficial mutation occurs before another beneficial allele on the same chromosome had time to reach fixation, then these two mutations can only be found in the same individual if recombination occurs. This concept is also conveyed by Gould when saying that &quot;selection creates the fit&quot;. But I still don&#39;t understand why the <b>additive genetic variance for fitness<\/b> increases as a result of recombination."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":15232,"edited":false,"creation_date":1393163080,"comment_id":20456,"body":"Its tough to write answers here - remember that responders want to explain terms to other readers as well as the poster or they get complaints.  I thought I&#39;d answered your question though.  Beneficial recombinations are <i>among<\/i> offspring; the vast majority of recombinations are probably less fit or have no substantial effect on fitness. Over time selection brings those combinations into common occurrence in the gene pool.  I didn&#39;t explain how selection works... maybe i need to define that in detail too?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":15232,"edited":false,"creation_date":1393205322,"comment_id":20484,"body":"Well the issue I&#39;m struggling with is the idea that fitness variance is greater in a population where recombination occurs. This is not intuitive to me. I understand that recombination allows to bring to fixation several mutations that occurs in different individuals in roughly speaking the same time (It actually depends on the probability to occur in a chromosome already bearing the mutation which depends on the time difference between the two mutations and the selective coefficient of the first according to Haldane&#39;s law 1-P = exp((1+s)p)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":15232,"edited":false,"creation_date":1393205399,"comment_id":20485,"body":"@s