7066953,"answer_count":2,"title":"Heterozygosity under genetic drift","body":"<p>The wright-Fisher model of genetic drift is:<\/p>\n\n<p>$$p_{ij} = \\binom{2N}{j}\\left(\\frac{i}{2N}\\right)^j \\left(1- \\frac{i}{2N}\\right)^{2N-j} $$<\/p>\n\n<p>,where $\\binom{2N}{j}$ is a binomial coefficient.<\/p>\n\n<p>From this equation one can infer that the expected heterozygostiy should decrease by $1-\\frac{1}{2N}$ at each time step because:<\/p>\n\n<p>$$E[x_{t+1}(1-x_{t+1}) \\space|\\space x_t] = (1-\\frac{1}{2N})x_t(1-x_t)$$<\/p>\n\n<p>I don't understand this equality. That might be very simple though! Can you help me making sense of it?<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://books.google.ch/books/about/Mathematical_Population_Genetics_1.html?id=twXIyXyod2MC&amp;redir_esc=y\" rel=\"nofollow\">source<\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":16448,"tags":["evolution","genetics","natural-selection","mathematical-models","population-biology"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":16487,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":99,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1397298590},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/1238748458/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":5578,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5578/tschoppi","reputation":217,"display_name":"tschoppi"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/1238748458/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":5578,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5578/tschoppi","reputation":217,"display_name":"tschoppi"},"score":1,"post_id":16523,"edited":false,"creation_date":1397407707,"comment_id":22295,"body":"Note: When answering this question, please back up your claims with references to the scientific literature.  (This is not a homework question [although phrased like one] but arose purely from personal interest and lack of time to pursue it properly.)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"l