unt like you are describing. You might also do this if you were studying the microbiology of an oil spill in water.<\/p>\n\n<p>There is nothing saying you could not suspend a sample in oil. There may even be a unknown benefit of using this method in certain circumstances, that is waiting to be discovered.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16480,"question_id":16432,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16432/can-oil-be-used-instead-of-water-in-preparing-wet-mounts-for-microscopy","last_activity_date":1397229820,"creation_date":1397008767,"answer_count":1,"title":"Can oil be used instead of water in preparing wet mounts for microscopy?","body":"<p>Is there a reason that oil (e.g., vegetable or clear mineral) is not used to make wet mounts in microscopy? I am not referring to oil immersion technique but substituting oil for water in wet mounts in bright field microscopy. <\/p>\n\n<p>The question is mostly about moss or mold, things that appear plantlike on a slide. The optical properties may be good and the viscosity, as with glycerine, gives a little depth to the slide. Maybe it causes some sort of distortion? I don't see this listed as a suggestion on microscopy sites. <\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks. <\/p>\n","question_id":16432,"tags":["mycology","microscopy"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":263,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/OFLQf.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6256,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6256/mhmd","reputation":108,"display_name":"Mhmd"},"closed_date":1397524002,"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/100005715270884/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":6291,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6291/beo","reputation":192,"display_name":"Beo"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/79614cc5fcd376b95171a5c8f6354e8a?s=128&d=identicon&r