nough but since you are only considering species interactions and not the impact of the abiotic environment you are describing community-level organization and not ecosystem level organization."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":16456,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d5e8817011bf40f20c518af3c0dc7187?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":137,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/137/kennypeanuts","reputation":1522,"display_name":"KennyPeanuts","accept_rate":75},"edited":false,"creation_date":1397228855,"comment_id":22238,"body":"What non-artificial environments do not have ecosystems and interdependencies?  at some level the laws that biology works with are a reasonable explanation."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1397086838,"creation_date":1397086838,"body":"<p>The definition of ecosystem here is missing, but if you mean \"an inter-dependency of different organisms that all live in the same geographic region\" then I think that competition and cooperation are big drivers of the establishment of these roles.<\/p>\n\n<p>Some animals and plants are so interdependent that they evolve together despite being different species.  The hawk moths have terribly long probiscus which are co-evolved with flowers with deep cup shapes.  <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/IXN6r.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>The flowers and the moths create more exclusive relationships - the flowers are more reliable food sources for the adult moths when other pollinators can't get to them and the flowers are more likely to succeed in pollination with the moth feeding of fewer kinds of flowers.  Cooperation of this nature tends to be show up spontaneously in the ecological milieu because of the utility and stability it can bring. <\/p>\n\n<p>Competition is the other side to this side of ecosystem evolution.  Because living things reproduce to the point where nutrition and security are scarce (meaning that there isn't enough for every plant/animal) cooperation becomes an important advantage.  <\/p>\n","answer_id":16456,"question_id":16444,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16444/why-are-there-ecosystems","last_activity_date":1397088628,"creation_date":1397061277,"answer_count":3,"title":"Why are there ecosystems?","body":"<p>Why would things self-organize in such a manner? I'm a mathematician and I have no baggage in ecology or biology. If the question is too broad maybe someone can point me to formal sources where this type of issues are tackled.<\/p>\n","question_id":16444,"tags":["zoology","botany","ecology"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":410,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/22dd873f32be2ca0a110a7131465eb13?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1439,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1439/po-jen-lai","reputation":36,"display_name":"Po-Jen Lai"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":1,"post_id":3646,"edited":false,"creation_date":1348312131,"comment_id":5518,"body":"You have to consider that there are plenty of voltage-sensitive channels that will open at 0mV so, no, you will not be likely to have an equilibrium at 0mV with the &quot;classic&quot; amount and type of channels on the membrane."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/22dd873f32be2ca0a110a7131465eb13?s=128&d=ident