"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5771/stords","reputation":729,"display_name":"stords"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1396748608,"creation_date":1396748608,"body":"<p>I would assume that the labeling occurs in the reduction of NTPs to form dNTPS.<\/p>\n\n<p>This process (catalyzed by <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ribonucleotide_reductase\" rel=\"nofollow\">ribonucleotide reductase<\/a>) involves protonating the hydroxyl group on the 2' carbon, allowing it to leave as water, and then adding a hydride to the newly formed carbocation. The two hydrogen atoms (the proton and the hydride) come from two thiols on the enzyme, which in the process are oxidized to form a disulfide bond.<\/p>\n\n<p>The crux is that, in the presence of heavy water, the two thiols would rapidly exchange their hydrogen for deuterium. That means that the hydride that gets added to the carbocation would be a deuterium, and the resulting dNTP would be deuterium labeled.<\/p>\n\n<p>This is the only step that I can imagine the labeling working for, as a carbon-hydrogen bond is formed (which doesn't exchange rapidly with the solvent) using the hydrogen from a sulfer-hydrogen bond (which does exchange rapidly with the solvent). <\/p>\n","answer_id":16364,"question_id":9414,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9414/what-is-the-mechanism-of-labeling-a-dna-molecule-with-deuterated-water","last_activity_date":1396748608,"creation_date":1374700705,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the mechanism of labeling a DNA molecule with deuterated water?","body":"<p>I have seen a paper in which deuterated water was used to follow dividing cells. The assumption was that deuterated water will be incorporated into newly synthesized DNA molecules. Is there any direct incorporation of water in the replication process? Is there any proton exchange?<\/p>\n\n<p>The paper describing the method can be found here:\n<a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/105/16/6115.full.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.pnas.org/content/105/16/6115.full.pdf<\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":9414,"tags":["dna","replication"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":138,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1374742987},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9c5a4ffba46514acb26f57f44b8b3043?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":566,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/566/caeruleus","reputation":348,"display_name":"caeruleus"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/53c30bc1f1ac4e6b256e52b62124da86?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1757,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1757/androidpenguin","reputation":4652,"display_name":"AndroidPenguin","accept_rate":25},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1396743787,"creation_date":1396743787,"body":"<p>The sensory and motor components are  required (GP and vagus respectively). Similar to the corneal reflex and cranial nerve 5 and 7, if a lesion exists in either the sensory or motor component there will be a defect. In your case, there is no motor innervation on the left due to the lack of the vagus nerve so there is no vagus nerve response. <\/p>\n","answer_id":16361,"question_id":16354,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16354/a-question-about-gag-reflex","last_activity_date":1396743787,"creation_date":1396706445,"answer_count":1,"title":"A question about gag reflex","body":"<p>If left glossopharyngeal nerve and right vagus nerve are intact, but there is a lesion at left vagus nerve, would stimulating the left side of pharynx elicit a gag reflex?<\/p>\n","question_id":16354,"tags":["neurology","medicine"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":16361,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":37,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b80be85e02e9346